SIMPLE: short
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Short
<hw>Short</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Shorter</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Shortest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>short</ets>,
<ets>schort</ets>, AS. <ets>scort</ets>, <ets>sceort</ets>; akin to OHG.
<ets>scurz</ets>, Icel. <ets>skorta</ets> to be short of, to lack, and
perhaps to E. <ets>shear</ets>, v. t. Cf. <er>Shirt</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Not long; having brief length or linear extension;
<as>as, a <ex>short</ex> distance; a <ex>short</ex> piece of timber; a
<ex>short</ex> flight.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bed is <qex>shorter</qex> than that a man can stretch himself
on it.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. xxviii. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not extended in time; having very limited duration;
not protracted; <as>as, <ex>short</ex> breath</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The life so <qex>short</qex>, the craft so long to learn.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>short</qex> absense I could yield.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Limited in quantity; inadequate; insufficient;
scanty; <as>as, a <ex>short</ex> supply of provisions, or of
water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Insufficiently provided; inadequately supplied;
scantily furnished; lacking; not coming up to a reasonable, or the
ordinary, standard; -- usually with <xex>of</xex>; <as>as, to be
<ex>short</ex> of money</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We shall be <qex>short</qex> in our provision.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Deficient; defective; imperfect; not coming up, as
to a measure or standard; <as>as, an account which is <ex>short</ex> of
the truth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Not distant in time; near at hand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Marinell was sore offended⟦br⟧
That his departure thence should be so <qex>short</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He commanded those who were appointed to attend him to be ready by
a <qex>short</qex> day.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Limited in intellectual power or grasp; not
comprehensive; narrow; not tenacious, as memory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their own <qex>short</qex> understandings reach⟦br⟧
No farther than the present.</q> <rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Less important, efficacious, or powerful; not equal
or equivalent; less (than); -- with <xex>of</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hardly anything <qex>short</qex> of an invasion could rouse them
again to war.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Abrupt; brief; pointed; petulant; <as>as, he gave a
<ex>short</ex> answer to the question</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Cookery)</fld> <def>Breaking or crumbling readily
in the mouth; crisp; <as>as, <ex>short</ex> pastry</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Metal)</fld> <def>Brittle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Metals that are brittle when hot are called
<xex><?/ot-short</xex>; as, cast iron may be <xex>hot-short</xex>, owing
to the presence of sulphur. Those that are brittle when cold are called
<xex>cold-short</xex>; as, cast iron may be <xex>cold-short</xex>, on
account of the presence of phosphorus.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Stock Exchange)</fld> <def>Engaging or engaged to
deliver what is not possessed; <as>as, <ex>short</ex> contracts; to be
<ex>short</ex> of stock. See <ex>The shorts</ex>, under <er>Short</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, and <ex>To sell short</ex>, under <er>Short</er>,
<pos>adv.</pos></as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In mercantile transactions, a note or bill is sometimes
made payable <xex>at short sight</xex>, that is, in a little time after
being presented to the payer.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>Not prolonged, or relatively
less prolonged, in utterance; -- opposed to <ant>long</ant>, and applied
to vowels or to syllables. In English, the long and short of the same
letter are not, in most cases, the long and short of the same sound;
thus, the <xex>i</xex> in <xex>ill</xex> is the short sound, not of
<xex>i</xex> in <xex>isle</xex>, but of <xex>ee</xex> in <xex>eel</xex>,
and the <xex>e</xex> in <xex>pet</xex> is the short sound of
<xex>a</xex> in <xex>pate</xex>, etc. See <er>Quantity</er>, and
<xex>Guide to Pronunciation</xex>, ⟦sect⟧⟦sect⟧22, 30.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Short</xex> is much used with participles to form
numerous self-explaining compounds; as, <xex>short</xex>-armed,
<xex>short</xex>-billed, <xex>short</xex>-fingered,
<xex>short</xex>-haired, <xex>short</xex>-necked,
<xex>short</xex>-sleeved, <xex>short</xex>-tailed,
<xex>short</xex>-winged, <xex>short</xex>-wooled, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>At short notice</b></col>, <cd>in a brief time;
promptly.</cd> -- <col><b>Short rib</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>,
<cd>one of the false ribs.</cd> -- <col><b>Short suit</b></col>
<fld>(Whist)</fld>, <cd>any suit having only three cards, or less than
three.</cd> <au>R. A. Proctor.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>To come
short</b></col>, <col><b>To cut short</b></col>, <col><b>To fall
short</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Come</er>, <er>Cut</er>,
etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Short</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Short
<hw>Short</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A summary
account.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>short</qex> and the long is, our play is preferred.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The part of milled grain sifted out
which is next finer than the bran.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The first remove above bran is <qex>shorts</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Halliwell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Short, inferior hemp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Breeches; shortclothes.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Phonetics)</fld> <def>A short sound, syllable, or
vowel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If we compare the nearest conventional <qex>shorts</qex> and longs
in English, as in ⟦ldquo⟧bit⟦rdquo⟧ and ⟦ldquo⟧beat,⟦rdquo⟧
⟦ldquo⟧not⟦rdquo⟧ and ⟦ldquo⟧naught,⟦rdquo⟧ we find that the short
vowels are generally wide, the long narrow, besides being generally
diphthongic as well. Hence, originally short vowels can be lengthened
and yet kept quite distinct from the original longs.</q> <rj><qau>H.
Sweet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In short</b></col>, <cd>in few words; in brief;
briefly.</cd> -- <col><b>The long and the short</b></col>, <cd>the
whole; a brief summing up.</cd> -- <col><b>The shorts</b></col>
<fld>(Stock Exchange)</fld>, <cd>those who are unsupplied with stocks
which they contracted to deliver.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Short</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Short
<hw>Short</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a short manner;
briefly; limitedly; abruptly; quickly; <as>as, to stop <ex>short</ex> in
one's course; to turn <ex>short</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was taken up very <qex>short</qex>, and adjudged corrigible for
such presumptuous language.</q> <rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To sell short</b></col> <fld>(Stock Exchange)</fld>,
<cd>to sell, for future delivery, what the party selling does not own,
but hopes to buy at a lower rate.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Short</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Short
<hw>Short</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>sceortian</ets>.]</ety>
<def>To shorten.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Short</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Short
<hw>Short</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To fail; to decrease.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shortage</ent>⟦br⟧
